name: Thing
description: The most generic type of item.

children.name: Action
children.description: An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role...

children.name: AchieveAction
children.description: The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.

children.name: LoseAction
children.description: The act of being defeated in a competitive activity.

children.name: TieAction
children.description: The act of reaching a draw in a competitive activity.

children.name: WinAction
children.description: The act of achieving victory in a competitive activity.

children.name: AssessAction
children.description: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

children.name: ChooseAction
children.description: The act of expressing a preference from a set of options or a large or unbounded set of choices/options.

children.name: VoteAction
children.description: The act of expressing a preference from a fixed/finite/structured set of choices/options.

children.name: IgnoreAction
children.description: The act of intentionally disregarding the object. An agent ignores an object.

children.name: ReactAction
children.description: The act of responding instinctively and emotionally to an object, expressing a sentiment.

children.name: AgreeAction
children.description: The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

children.name: DisagreeAction
children.description: The act of expressing a difference of opinion with the object. An agent disagrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

children.name: DislikeAction
children.description: The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

children.name: EndorseAction
children.description: An agent approves/certifies/likes/supports/sanctions an object.

children.name: LikeAction
children.description: The act of expressing a positive sentiment about the object. An agent likes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

children.name: WantAction
children.description: The act of expressing a desire about the object. An agent wants an object.

children.name: ReviewAction
children.description: The act of producing a balanced opinion about the object for an audience. An agent reviews an object with participants resulting in a review.

children.name: ConsumeAction
children.description: The act of ingesting information/resources/food.

children.name: DrinkAction
children.description: The act of swallowing liquids.

children.name: EatAction
children.description: The act of swallowing solid objects.

children.name: InstallAction
children.description: The act of installing an application.

children.name: ListenAction
children.description: The act of consuming audio content.

children.name: PlayGameAction
children.description: The act of playing a video game.

children.name: ReadAction
children.description: The act of consuming written content.

children.name: UseAction
children.description: The act of applying an object to its intended purpose.

children.name: WearAction
children.description: The act of dressing oneself in clothing.

children.name: ViewAction
children.description: The act of consuming static visual content.

children.name: WatchAction
children.description: The act of consuming dynamic/moving visual content.

children.name: ControlAction
children.description: An agent controls a device or application.

children.name: ActivateAction
children.description: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).

children.name: DeactivateAction
children.description: The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).

children.name: ResumeAction
children.description: The act of resuming a device or application which was formerly paused (e.g. resume music playback or resume a timer).

children.name: SuspendAction
children.description: The act of momentarily pausing a device or application (e.g. pause music playback or pause a timer).

children.name: CreateAction
children.description: The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.

children.name: CookAction
children.description: The act of producing/preparing food.

children.name: DrawAction
children.description: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

children.name: FilmAction
children.description: The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.

children.name: PaintAction
children.description: The act of producing a painting, typically with paint and canvas as instruments.

children.name: PhotographAction
children.description: The act of capturing still images of objects using a camera.

children.name: WriteAction
children.description: The act of authoring written creative content.

children.name: FindAction
children.description:
The act of finding an object.

Related actions:


SearchAction: FindAction is generally lead by a SearchAction, but not necessarily.

children.name: CheckAction
children.description: An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.

children.name: DiscoverAction
children.description: The act of discovering/finding an object.

children.name: TrackAction
children.description:
An agent tracks an object for updates.

Related actions:


FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, TrackAction refers to the interest on the location of innanimates objects.
SubscribeAction: Unlike SubscribeAction, TrackAction refers to  the interest on the location of innanimate objects.

children.name: InteractAction
children.description: The act of interacting with another person or organization.

children.name: BefriendAction
children.description:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically.

Related actions:


FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, BefriendAction implies that the connection is reciprocal.

children.name: CommunicateAction
children.description: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.

children.name: AskAction
children.description:
The act of posing a question / favor to someone.

Related actions:


ReplyAction: Appears generally as a response to AskAction.

children.name: CheckInAction
children.description:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check-in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc).

Related actions:


CheckOutAction: The antonym of CheckInAction...

children.name: CheckOutAction
children.description:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check-in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:


CheckInAction: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
DepartAction: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service...

children.name: CommentAction
children.description: The act of generating a comment about a subject.

children.name: InformAction
children.description: The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.

children.name: ConfirmAction
children.description:
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:


CancelAction: The antonym of ConfirmAction.

children.name: RsvpAction
children.description: The act of notifying an event organizer as to whether you expect to attend the event.

children.name: InviteAction
children.description: The act of asking someone to attend an event. Reciprocal of RsvpAction.

children.name: ReplyAction
children.description:
The act of responding to a question/message asked/sent by the object. Related to AskAction.

Related actions:


AskAction: Appears generally as an origin of a ReplyAction.

children.name: ShareAction
children.description: The act of distributing content to people for their amusement or edification.

children.name: FollowAction
children.description:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:


BefriendAction: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is not necessarily reciprocal...

children.name: JoinAction
children.description:
An agent joins an event/group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:


RegisterAction: Unlike RegisterAction, JoinAction refers to joining a group/team of people.
SubscribeAction: Unlike SubscribeAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be receiving updates...

children.name: LeaveAction
children.description:
An agent leaves an event / group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:


JoinAction: The antonym of LeaveAction.
UnRegisterAction: Unlike UnRegisterAction, LeaveAction implies leaving a group/team of people rather than a service.

children.name: MarryAction
children.description: The act of marrying a person.

children.name: RegisterAction
children.description:
The act of registering to be a user of a service, product or web page.

Related actions:


JoinAction: Unlike JoinAction, RegisterAction implies you are registering to be a user of a service, not a group/team of people.
FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting to poll for updates from the object...

children.name: SubscribeAction
children.description:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates pushed to.

Related actions:


FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, SubscribeAction implies that the subscriber acts as a passive agent being constantly/actively pushed for updates...

children.name: UnRegisterAction
children.description:
The act of un-registering from a service.

Related actions:


RegisterAction: antonym of UnRegisterAction.
LeaveAction: Unlike LeaveAction, UnRegisterAction implies that you are unregistering from a service you were previously registered, rather than leaving a team/group of people.

children.name: MoveAction
children.description:
The act of an agent relocating to a place.

Related actions:


TransferAction: Unlike TransferAction, the subject of the move is a living Person or Organization rather than an inanimate object.

children.name: ArriveAction
children.description: The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from a fromLocation, optionally with participants.

children.name: DepartAction
children.description: The act of  departing from a place. An agent departs from a fromLocation for a destination, optionally with participants.

children.name: TravelAction
children.description: The act of traveling from a fromLocation to a destination by a specified mode of transport, optionally with participants.

children.name: OrganizeAction
children.description: The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.

children.name: AllocateAction
children.description: The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.

children.name: AcceptAction
children.description:
The act of committing to/adopting an object.

Related actions:


RejectAction: The antonym of AcceptAction.

children.name: AssignAction
children.description: The act of allocating an action/event/task to some destination (someone or something).

children.name: AuthorizeAction
children.description: The act of granting permission to an object.

children.name: RejectAction
children.description:
The act of rejecting to/adopting an object.

Related actions:


AcceptAction: The antonym of RejectAction.

children.name: ApplyAction
children.description:
The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it.

Related actions:


RegisterAction: Unlike RegisterAction, ApplyAction has no guarantees that the application will be accepted.

children.name: BookmarkAction
children.description: An agent bookmarks/flags/labels/tags/marks an object.

children.name: PlanAction
children.description: The act of planning the execution of an event/task/action/reservation/plan to a future date.

children.name: CancelAction
children.description:
The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen.

Related actions:


ConfirmAction: The antonym of CancelAction.

children.name: ReserveAction
children.description:
Reserving a concrete object.

Related actions:


ScheduleAction: Unlike ScheduleAction, ReserveAction reserves concrete objects (e.g. a table, a hotel) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

children.name: ScheduleAction
children.description:
Scheduling future actions, events, or tasks.

Related actions:


ReserveAction: Unlike ReserveAction, ScheduleAction allocates future actions (e.g. an event, a task, etc) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

children.name: PlayAction
children.description:
The act of playing/exercising/training/performing for enjoyment, leisure, recreation, competition or exercise.

Related actions:


ListenAction: Unlike ListenAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to performing for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming music...

children.name: ExerciseAction
children.description: The act of participating in exertive activity for the purposes of improving health and fitness.

children.name: PerformAction
children.description: The act of participating in performance arts.

children.name: SearchAction
children.description:
The act of searching for an object.

Related actions:


FindAction: SearchAction generally leads to a FindAction, but not necessarily.

children.name: SeekToAction
children.description: This is the Action of navigating to a specific startOffset timestamp within a VideoObject, typically represented with a URL template structure.

children.name: SolveMathAction
children.description: The action that takes in a math expression and directs users to a page potentially capable of solving/simplifying that expression.

children.name: TradeAction
children.description: The act of participating in an exchange of goods and services for monetary compensation. An agent trades an object, product or service with a participant in exchange for a one time or periodic payment.

children.name: BuyAction
children.description: The act of giving money to a seller in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent buys an object, product, or service from a seller for a price. Reciprocal of SellAction.

children.name: DonateAction
children.description: The act of providing goods, services, or money without compensation, often for philanthropic reasons.

children.name: OrderAction
children.description: An agent orders an object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

children.name: PayAction
children.description: An agent pays a price to a participant.

children.name: PreOrderAction
children.description: An agent orders a (not yet released) object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

children.name: QuoteAction
children.description: An agent quotes/estimates/appraises an object/product/service with a price at a location/store.

children.name: RentAction
children.description: The act of giving money in return for temporary use, but not ownership, of an object such as a vehicle or property. For example, an agent rents a property from a landlord in exchange for a periodic payment.

children.name: SellAction
children.description: The act of taking money from a buyer in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent sells an object, product, or service to a buyer for a price. Reciprocal of BuyAction.

children.name: TipAction
children.description: The act of giving money voluntarily to a beneficiary in recognition of services rendered.

children.name: TransferAction
children.description: The act of transferring/moving (abstract or concrete) animate or inanimate objects from one place to another.

children.name: BorrowAction
children.description:
The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction.

Related actions:


LendAction: Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

children.name: DownloadAction
children.description: The act of downloading an object.

children.name: GiveAction
children.description:
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:


TakeAction: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
SendAction: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).

children.name: LendAction
children.description:
The act of providing an object under an agreement that it will be returned at a later date. Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

Related actions:


BorrowAction: Reciprocal of LendAction.

children.name: MoneyTransfer
children.description: The act of transferring money from one place to another place. This may occur electronically or physically.

children.name: ReceiveAction
children.description:
The act of physically/electronically taking delivery of an object that has been transferred from an origin to a destination. Reciprocal of SendAction.

Related actions:


SendAction: The reciprocal of ReceiveAction.
TakeAction: Unlike TakeAction, ReceiveAction does not imply that the ownership has been transferred (e...

children.name: ReturnAction
children.description: The act of returning to the origin that which was previously received (concrete objects) or taken (ownership).

children.name: SendAction
children.description:
The act of physically/electronically dispatching an object for transfer from an origin to a destination. Related actions:


ReceiveAction: The reciprocal of SendAction.
GiveAction: Unlike GiveAction, SendAction does not imply the transfer of ownership (e...

children.name: TakeAction
children.description:
The act of gaining ownership of an object from an origin. Reciprocal of GiveAction.

Related actions:


GiveAction: The reciprocal of TakeAction.
ReceiveAction: Unlike ReceiveAction, TakeAction implies that ownership has been transferred.

children.name: UpdateAction
children.description: The act of managing by changing/editing the state of the object.

children.name: AddAction
children.description: The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.

children.name: InsertAction
children.description: The act of adding at a specific location in an ordered collection.

children.name: AppendAction
children.description: The act of inserting at the end if an ordered collection.

children.name: PrependAction
children.description: The act of inserting at the beginning if an ordered collection.

children.name: DeleteAction
children.description: The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.

children.name: ReplaceAction
children.description: The act of editing a recipient by replacing an old object with a new object.

children.name: BioChemEntity
children.description: Any biological, chemical, or biochemical thing. For example: a protein; a gene; a chemical; a synthetic chemical.

children.name: ChemicalSubstance
children.description: A chemical substance is 'a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types' (source: ChEBI:59999).

children.name: Gene
children.description: A discrete unit of inheritance which affects one or more biological traits (Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene). Examples include FOXP2 (Forkhead box protein P2), SCARNA21 (small Cajal body-specific RNA 21), A- (agouti genotype).

children.name: MolecularEntity
children.description: Any constitutionally or isotopically distinct atom, molecule, ion, ion pair, radical, radical ion, complex, conformer etc., identifiable as a separately distinguishable entity.

children.name: Protein
children.description: Protein is here used in its widest possible definition, as classes of amino acid based molecules. Amyloid-beta Protein in human (UniProt P05067), eukaryota (e.g. an OrthoDB group) or even a single molecule that one can point to are all of type schema:Protein...

children.name: CreativeWork
children.description: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

children.name: AmpStory
children.description: A creative work with a visual storytelling format intended to be viewed online, particularly on mobile devices.

children.name: ArchiveComponent
children.description: An intangible type to be applied to any archive content, carrying with it a set of properties required to describe archival items and collections.

children.name: Article
children.description:
An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.

See also blog post.

children.name: AdvertiserContentArticle
children.description: An Article that an external entity has paid to place or to produce to its specifications. Includes advertorials, sponsored content, native advertising and other paid content.

children.name: NewsArticle
children.description:
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of schema.org News markup is also available.

children.name: AnalysisNewsArticle
children.description: An AnalysisNewsArticle is a NewsArticle that, while based on factual reporting, incorporates the expertise of the author/producer, offering interpretations and conclusions.

children.name: AskPublicNewsArticle
children.description: A NewsArticle expressing an open call by a NewsMediaOrganization asking the public for input, insights, clarifications, anecdotes, documentation, etc., on an issue, for reporting purposes.

children.name: BackgroundNewsArticle
children.description: A NewsArticle providing historical context, definition and detail on a specific topic (aka "explainer" or "backgrounder"). For example, an in-depth article or frequently-asked-questions (FAQ) document on topics such as Climate Change or the European Union...

children.name: OpinionNewsArticle
children.description: An OpinionNewsArticle is a NewsArticle that primarily expresses opinions rather than journalistic reporting of news and events. For example, a NewsArticle consisting of a column or Blog/BlogPosting entry in the Opinions section of a news publication.

children.name: ReportageNewsArticle
children.description:
The ReportageNewsArticle type is a subtype of NewsArticle representing
 news articles which are the result of journalistic news reporting conventions.

In practice many news publishers produce a wide variety of article types, many of which might be considered a NewsArticle but not a ReportageNewsArticle...

children.name: ReviewNewsArticle
children.description: A NewsArticle and CriticReview providing a professional critic's assessment of a service, product, performance, or artistic or literary work.

children.name: Report
children.description: A Report generated by governmental or non-governmental organization.

children.name: SatiricalArticle
children.description: An Article whose content is primarily [satirical] in nature, i.e. unlikely to be literally true. A satirical article is sometimes but not necessarily also a NewsArticle. ScholarlyArticles are also sometimes satirized.

children.name: ScholarlyArticle
children.description: A scholarly article.

children.name: MedicalScholarlyArticle
children.description: A scholarly article in the medical domain.

children.name: SocialMediaPosting
children.description: A post to a social media platform, including blog posts, tweets, Facebook posts, etc.

children.name: BlogPosting
children.description: A blog post.

children.name: LiveBlogPosting
children.description: A LiveBlogPosting is a BlogPosting intended to provide a rolling textual coverage of an ongoing event through continuous updates.

children.name: DiscussionForumPosting
children.description: A posting to a discussion forum.

children.name: TechArticle
children.description: A technical article - Example: How-to (task) topics, step-by-step, procedural troubleshooting, specifications, etc.

children.name: APIReference
children.description: Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).

children.name: Atlas
children.description: A collection or bound volume of maps, charts, plates or tables, physical or in media form illustrating any subject.

children.name: Blog
children.description: A blog, sometimes known as a "weblog". Note that the individual posts (BlogPostings) in a Blog are often colloquially referred to by the same term.

children.name: Book
children.description: A book.

children.name: Audiobook
children.description: An audiobook.

children.name: Chapter
children.description: One of the sections into which a book is divided. A chapter usually has a section number or a name.

children.name: Claim
children.description: A Claim in Schema.org represents a specific, factually-oriented claim that could be the itemReviewed in a ClaimReview. The content of a claim can be summarized with the text property. Variations on well known claims can have their common identity indicated via sameAs links, and summarized with a name...

children.name: Clip
children.description: A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.

children.name: MovieClip
children.description: A short segment/part of a movie.

children.name: RadioClip
children.description: A short radio program or a segment/part of a radio program.

children.name: TVClip
children.description: A short TV program or a segment/part of a TV program.

children.name: VideoGameClip
children.description: A short segment/part of a video game.

children.name: Code
children.description: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

children.name: Collection
children.description: A collection of items, e.g. creative works or products.

children.name: ProductCollection
children.description: A set of products (either ProductGroups or specific variants) that are listed together e.g. in an Offer.

children.name: ComicStory
children.description:
The term "story" is any indivisible, re-printable
        unit of a comic, including the interior stories, covers, and backmatter. Most
        comics have at least two stories: a cover (ComicCoverArt) and an interior story.

children.name: ComicCoverArt
children.description: The artwork on the cover of a comic.

children.name: Comment
children.description: A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the text property, and its topic via about, properties shared with all CreativeWorks.

children.name: Answer
children.description: An answer offered to a question; perhaps correct, perhaps opinionated or wrong.

children.name: CorrectionComment
children.description: A comment that corrects CreativeWork.

children.name: Question
children.description: A specific question - e.g. from a user seeking answers online, or collected in a Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) document.

children.name: Conversation
children.description: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.

children.name: Course
children.description: A description of an educational course which may be offered as distinct instances which take place at different times or take place at different locations, or be offered through different media or modes of study. An educational course is a sequence of one or more educational events and/or creative works which aims to build knowledge, competence or ability of learners.

children.name: CreativeWorkSeason
children.description: A media season, e.g. TV, radio, video game etc.

children.name: PodcastSeason
children.description: A single season of a podcast. Many podcasts do not break down into separate seasons. In that case, PodcastSeries should be used.

children.name: RadioSeason
children.description: Season dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

children.name: TVSeason
children.description: Season dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

children.name: CreativeWorkSeries
children.description: A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike ItemList which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e...

children.name: BookSeries
children.description: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.

children.name: MovieSeries
children.description: A series of movies. Included movies can be indicated with the hasPart property.

children.name: Periodical
children.description:
A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended to continue indefinitely, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper.

See also blog post.

children.name: ComicSeries
children.description:
A sequential publication of comic stories under a
        unifying title, for example "The Amazing Spider-Man" or "Groo the
        Wanderer".

children.name: Newspaper
children.description: A publication containing information about varied topics that are pertinent to general information, a geographic area, or a specific subject matter (i.e. business, culture, education). Often published daily.

children.name: PodcastSeries
children.description: A podcast is an episodic series of digital audio or video files which a user can download and listen to.

children.name: RadioSeries
children.description: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

children.name: TVSeries
children.description: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

children.name: VideoGameSeries
children.description: A video game series.

children.name: DataCatalog
children.description: A collection of datasets.

children.name: Dataset
children.description: A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.

children.name: DataFeed
children.description: A single feed providing structured information about one or more entities or topics.

children.name: CompleteDataFeed
children.description:
A CompleteDataFeed is a DataFeed whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving RFC 5005, for example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e...

children.name: DefinedTermSet
children.description: A set of defined terms, for example a set of categories or a classification scheme, a glossary, dictionary or enumeration.

children.name: CategoryCodeSet
children.description: A set of Category Code values.

children.name: Diet
children.description: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

children.name: DigitalDocument
children.description: An electronic file or document.

children.name: NoteDigitalDocument
children.description: A file containing a note, primarily for the author.

children.name: PresentationDigitalDocument
children.description: A file containing slides or used for a presentation.

children.name: SpreadsheetDigitalDocument
children.description: A spreadsheet file.

children.name: TextDigitalDocument
children.description: A file composed primarily of text.

children.name: Drawing
children.description: A picture or diagram made with a pencil, pen, or crayon rather than paint.

children.name: EducationalOccupationalCredential
children.description: An educational or occupational credential. A diploma, academic degree, certification, qualification, badge, etc., that may be awarded to a person or other entity that meets the requirements defined by the credentialer.

children.name: Episode
children.description: A media episode (e.g. TV, radio, video game) which can be part of a series or season.

children.name: PodcastEpisode
children.description: A single episode of a podcast series.

children.name: RadioEpisode
children.description: A radio episode which can be part of a series or season.

children.name: TVEpisode
children.description: A TV episode which can be part of a series or season.

children.name: ExercisePlan
children.description: Fitness-related activity designed for a specific health-related purpose, including defined exercise routines as well as activity prescribed by a clinician.

children.name: Game
children.description: The Game type represents things which are games. These are typically rule-governed recreational activities, e.g. role-playing games in which players assume the role of characters in a fictional setting.

children.name: VideoGame
children.description: A video game is an electronic game that involves human interaction with a user interface to generate visual feedback on a video device.

children.name: Guide
children.description: Guide is a page or article that recommends specific products or services, or aspects of a thing for a user to consider. A Guide may represent a Buying Guide and detail aspects of products or services for a user to consider. A Guide may represent a Product Guide and recommend specific products or services...

children.name: HowTo
children.description: Instructions that explain how to achieve a result by performing a sequence of steps.

children.name: Recipe
children.description: A recipe. For dietary restrictions covered by the recipe, a few common restrictions are enumerated via suitableForDiet. The keywords property can also be used to add more detail.

children.name: HowToDirection
children.description: A direction indicating a single action to do in the instructions for how to achieve a result.

children.name: HowToSection
children.description: A sub-grouping of steps in the instructions for how to achieve a result (e.g. steps for making a pie crust within a pie recipe).

children.name: HowToStep
children.description: A step in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It is an ordered list with HowToDirection and/or HowToTip items.

children.name: HowToTip
children.description: An explanation in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It provides supplementary information about a technique, supply, author's preference, etc. It can explain what could be done, or what should not be done, but doesn't specify what should be done (see HowToDirection).

children.name: HyperToc
children.description: A HyperToc represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as VideoObject, AudioObject. For cases where the same larger work is split into multiple files, associatedMedia can be used on individual HyperTocEntry items.

children.name: HyperTocEntry
children.description: A HyperToEntry is an item within a HyperToc, which represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as VideoObject, AudioObject. The media object itself is indicated using associatedMedia. Each section of interest within that content can be described with a HyperTocEntry, with associated startOffset and endOffset...

children.name: LearningResource
children.description:
The LearningResource type can be used to indicate CreativeWorks (whether physical or digital) that have a particular and explicit orientation towards learning, education, skill acquisition, and other educational purposes.

LearningResource is expected to be used as an addition to a primary type such as Book, VideoObject, Product etc...

children.name: Course
children.description: A description of an educational course which may be offered as distinct instances which take place at different times or take place at different locations, or be offered through different media or modes of study. An educational course is a sequence of one or more educational events and/or creative works which aims to build knowledge, competence or ability of learners.

children.name: Quiz
children.description: Quiz: A test of knowledge, skills and abilities.

children.name: Legislation
children.description: A legal document such as an act, decree, bill, etc. (enforceable or not) or a component of a legal act (like an article).

children.name: LegislationObject
children.description: A specific object or file containing a Legislation. Note that the same Legislation can be published in multiple files. For example, a digitally signed PDF, a plain PDF and an HTML version.

children.name: Manuscript
children.description: A book, document, or piece of music written by hand rather than typed or printed.

children.name: Map
children.description: A map.

children.name: MathSolver
children.description: A math solver which is capable of solving a subset of mathematical problems.

children.name: MediaObject
children.description: A media object, such as an image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset, i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObjects).

children.name: 3DModel
children.description: A 3D model represents some kind of 3D content, which may have encodings in one or more MediaObjects. Many 3D formats are available (e.g. see Wikipedia); specific encoding formats can be represented using the encodingFormat property applied to the relevant MediaObject...

children.name: AmpStory
children.description: A creative work with a visual storytelling format intended to be viewed online, particularly on mobile devices.

children.name: AudioObject
children.description: An audio file.

children.description: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of an AudioObject. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e...

children.name: Audiobook
children.description: An audiobook.

children.name: DataDownload
children.description: All or part of a Dataset in downloadable form.

children.name: ImageObject
children.description: An image file.

children.name: Barcode
children.description: An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.

children.name: ImageObjectSnapshot
children.description: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of an ImageObject. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. children.name: LegislationObject
children.description: A specific object or file containing a Legislation. Note that the same Legislation can be published in multiple files. For example, a digitally signed PDF, a plain PDF and an HTML version.

children.name: MusicVideoObject
children.description: A music video file.

children.name: VideoObject

children.name: VideoObjectSnapshot

children.name: MediaReviewItem
children.description: Represents an item or group of closely related items treated as a unit for the sake of evaluation in a MediaReview. Authorship etc. apply to the items rather than to the curation/grouping or reviewing party.

children.name: Menu
children.description: A structured representation of food or drink items available from a FoodEstablishment.

children.name: MenuSection
children.description: A sub-grouping of food or drink items in a menu. E.g. courses (such as 'Dinner', 'Breakfast', etc.), specific type of dishes (such as 'Meat', 'Vegan', 'Drinks', etc.), or some other classification made by the menu provider.

children.name: Message
children.description: A single message from a sender to one or more organizations or people.

children.name: EmailMessage
children.description: An email message.

children.name: Movie
children.description: A movie.

children.name: MusicComposition
children.description: A musical composition.

children.name: MusicPlaylist
children.description: A collection of music tracks in playlist form.

children.name: MusicAlbum
children.description: A collection of music tracks.

children.name: MusicRelease
children.description: A MusicRelease is a specific release of a music album.

children.name: MusicRecording
children.description: A music recording (track), usually a single song.

children.name: Painting
children.description: A painting.

children.name: Photograph
children.description: A photograph.

children.name: Play
children.description: A play is a form of literature, usually consisting of dialogue between characters, intended for theatrical performance rather than just reading. Note: A performance of a Play would be a TheaterEvent or BroadcastEvent - the Play being the workPerformed.

children.name: Poster
children.description: A large, usually printed placard, bill, or announcement, often illustrated, that is posted to advertise or publicize something.

children.name: PublicationIssue
children.description:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or publication volume, often numbered, usually containing a grouping of works such as articles.

See also blog post.

children.name: ComicIssue
children.description:
Individual comic issues are serially published as
        part of a larger series. For the sake of consistency, even one-shot issues
        belong to a series comprised of a single issue. All comic issues can be
        uniquely identified by: the combination of the name and volume number of the
        series to which the issue belongs; the issue number; and the variant
        description of the issue (if any).

children.name: PublicationVolume
children.description:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or multi-volume work, often numbered. It may represent a time span, such as a year.

See also blog post.

children.name: Quotation
children.description: A quotation. Often but not necessarily from some written work, attributable to a real world author and - if associated with a fictional character - to any fictional Person. Use isBasedOn to link to source/origin. The recordedIn property can be used to reference a Quotation from an Event.

children.name: Review
children.description: A review of an item - for example, of a restaurant, movie, or store.

children.name: ClaimReview
children.description: A fact-checking review of claims made (or reported) in some creative work (referenced via itemReviewed).

children.name: CriticReview
children.description: A CriticReview is a more specialized form of Review written or published by a source that is recognized for its reviewing activities. These can include online columns, travel and food guides, TV and radio shows, blogs and other independent Web sites. CriticReviews are typically more in-depth and professionally written...

children.name: ReviewNewsArticle
children.description: A NewsArticle and CriticReview providing a professional critic's assessment of a service, product, performance, or artistic or literary work.

children.name: EmployerReview
children.description: An EmployerReview is a review of an Organization regarding its role as an employer, written by a current or former employee of that organization.

children.name: MediaReview
children.description:
A MediaReview is a more specialized form of Review dedicated to the evaluation of media content online, typically in the context of fact-checking and misinformation.
    For more general reviews of media in the broader sense, use UserReview, CriticReview or other Review types...

children.name: Recommendation
children.description: Recommendation is a type of Review that suggests or proposes something as the best option or best course of action. Recommendations may be for products or services, or other concrete things, as in the case of a ranked list or product guide. A Guide may list multiple recommendations for different categories...

children.name: UserReview
children.description: A review created by an end-user (e.g. consumer, purchaser, attendee etc.), in contrast with CriticReview.

children.name: Sculpture
children.description: A piece of sculpture.

children.name: Season
children.description: A media season, e.g. TV, radio, video game etc.

children.name: SheetMusic
children.description: Printed music, as opposed to performed or recorded music.

children.name: ShortStory
children.description: Short story or tale. A brief work of literature, usually written in narrative prose.

children.name: SoftwareApplication
children.description: A software application.

children.name: MobileApplication
children.description: A software application designed specifically to work well on a mobile device such as a telephone.

children.name: VideoGame
children.description: A video game is an electronic game that involves human interaction with a user interface to generate visual feedback on a video device.

children.name: WebApplication
children.description: Web applications.

children.name: SoftwareSourceCode
children.description: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

children.name: SpecialAnnouncement
children.description:
A SpecialAnnouncement combines a simple date-stamped textual information update
      with contextualized Web links and other structured data.  It represents an information update made by a
      locally-oriented organization, for example schools, pharmacies, healthcare providers,  community groups, police,
      local government...

children.name: Statement
children.description: A statement about something, for example a fun or interesting fact. If known, the main entity this statement is about can be indicated using mainEntity. For more formal claims (e.g. in Fact Checking), consider using Claim instead. Use the text property to capture the text of the statement.

children.name: TVSeason
children.description: Season dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

children.name: TVSeries
children.description: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

children.name: Thesis
children.description: A thesis or dissertation document submitted in support of candidature for an academic degree or professional qualification.

children.name: VisualArtwork
children.description: A work of art that is primarily visual in character.

children.name: CoverArt
children.description: The artwork on the outer surface of a CreativeWork.

children.name: ComicCoverArt
children.description: The artwork on the cover of a comic.

children.name: WebContent
children.description: WebContent is a type representing all WebPage, WebSite and WebPageElement content. It is sometimes the case that detailed distinctions between Web pages, sites and their parts are not always important or obvious. The  WebContent type makes it easier to describe Web-addressable content without requiring such distinctions to always be stated...

children.name: HealthTopicContent
children.description: HealthTopicContent is WebContent that is about some aspect of a health topic, e.g. a condition, its symptoms or treatments. Such content may be comprised of several parts or sections and use different types of media. Multiple instances of WebContent (and hence HealthTopicContent) can be related using hasPart / isPartOf where there is some kind of content hierarchy, and their content described with about and mentions e...

children.name: WebPage
children.description: A web page. Every web page is implicitly assumed to be declared to be of type WebPage, so the various properties about that webpage, such as breadcrumb may be used. We recommend explicit declaration if these properties are specified, but if they are found outside of an itemscope, they will be assumed to be about the page.

children.name: AboutPage
children.description: Web page type: About page.

children.name: CheckoutPage
children.description: Web page type: Checkout page.

children.name: CollectionPage
children.description: Web page type: Collection page.

children.name: MediaGallery
children.description: Web page type: Media gallery page. A mixed-media page that can contain media such as images, videos, and other multimedia.

children.name: ImageGallery
children.description: Web page type: Image gallery page.

children.name: VideoGallery
children.description: Web page type: Video gallery page.

children.name: ContactPage
children.description: Web page type: Contact page.

children.name: FAQPage
children.description: A FAQPage is a WebPage presenting one or more "Frequently asked questions" (see also QAPage).

children.name: ItemPage
children.description: A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.

children.name: MedicalWebPage
children.description: A web page that provides medical information.

children.name: ProfilePage
children.description: Web page type: Profile page.

children.name: QAPage
children.description: A QAPage is a WebPage focussed on a specific Question and its Answer(s), e.g. in a question answering site or documenting Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs).

children.name: RealEstateListing
children.description:
A RealEstateListing is a listing that describes one or more real-estate Offers (whose businessFunction is typically to lease out, or to sell).
  The RealEstateListing type itself represents the overall listing, as manifested in some WebPage.

children.name: SearchResultsPage
children.description: Web page type: Search results page.

children.name: WebPageElement
children.description: A web page element, like a table or an image.

children.name: SiteNavigationElement
children.description: A navigation element of the page.

children.name: Table
children.description: A table on a Web page.

children.name: WPAdBlock
children.description: An advertising section of the page.

children.name: WPFooter
children.description: The footer section of the page.

children.name: WPHeader
children.description: The header section of the page.

children.name: WPSideBar
children.description: A sidebar section of the page.

children.name: WebSite
children.description: A WebSite is a set of related web pages and other items typically served from a single web domain and accessible via URLs.

children.name: Event
children.description: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the offers property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

children.name: BusinessEvent
children.description: Event type: Business event.

children.name: ChildrensEvent
children.description: Event type: Children's event.

children.name: ComedyEvent
children.description: Event type: Comedy event.

children.name: CourseInstance
children.description: An instance of a Course which is distinct from other instances because it is offered at a different time or location or through different media or modes of study or to a specific section of students.

children.name: DanceEvent
children.description: Event type: A social dance.

children.name: DeliveryEvent
children.description: An event involving the delivery of an item.

children.name: EducationEvent
children.description: Event type: Education event.

children.name: EventSeries
children.description:
A series of Events. Included events can relate with the series using the superEvent property.

An EventSeries is a collection of events that share some unifying characteristic. For example, "The Olympic Games" is a series, which
is repeated regularly. The "2012 London Olympics" can be presented both as an Event in the series "Olympic Games", and as an
EventSeries that included a number of sporting competitions as Events...

children.name: ExhibitionEvent
children.description: Event type: Exhibition event, e.g. at a museum, library, archive, tradeshow, ...

children.name: Festival
children.description: Event type: Festival.

children.name: FoodEvent
children.description: Event type: Food event.

children.name: LiteraryEvent
children.description: Event type: Literary event.

children.name: MusicEvent
children.description: Event type: Music event.

children.description: A PublicationEvent corresponds indifferently to the event of publication for a CreativeWork of any type, e.g. a broadcast event, an on-demand event, a book/journal publication via a variety of delivery media.

children.name: BroadcastEvent
children.description: An over the air or online broadcast event.

children.name: OnDemandEvent
children.description: A publication event, e.g. catch-up TV or radio podcast, during which a program is available on-demand.

children.name: SaleEvent
children.description: Event type: Sales event.

children.name: ScreeningEvent
children.description: A screening of a movie or other video.

children.name: SocialEvent
children.description: Event type: Social event.

children.name: SportsEvent
children.description: Event type: Sports event.

children.name: TheaterEvent
children.description: Event type: Theater performance.

children.name: AlignmentObject
children.description:
An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.

children.name: Audience

children.description: A set of characteristics describing parents, who can be interested in viewing some content.

children.description: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also BedType (under development).

children.name: Brand
children.description: A brand is a name used by an organization or business person for labeling a product, product group, or similar.

children.name: BroadcastChannel
children.description: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

children.name: RadioChannel
children.description: A unique instance of a radio BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

children.description: The frequency in MHz and the modulation used for a particular BroadcastService.

children.name: DataFeedItem
children.description: A single item within a larger data feed.

children.name: DefinedTerm
children.description: A word, name, acronym, phrase, etc. with a formal definition. children.name: CategoryCode
children.description: A Category Code.

children.name: MedicalCode
children.description: A code for a medical entity.

children.name: Demand
children.description: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

children.description: A program with both an educational and employment component. Typically based at a workplace and structured around work-based learning, with the aim of instilling competencies related to an occupation. WorkBasedProgram is used to distinguish programs such as apprenticeships from school, college or other classroom based educational programs.

children.name: EnergyConsumptionDetails
children.description: EnergyConsumptionDetails represents information related to the energy efficiency of a product that consumes energy. The information that can be provided is based on international regulations such as for example EU directive 2017/1369 for energy labeling and the Energy labeling rule under the Energy Policy and Conservation Act (EPCA) in the US.

children.name: EntryPoint
children.description: An entry point, within some Web-based protocol.

children.name: Enumeration
children.description: Lists or enumerations—for example, a list of cuisines or music genres, etc.

children.name: AdultOrientedEnumeration
children.description: Enumeration of considerations that make a product relevant or potentially restricted for adults only.

children.name: BoardingPolicyType
children.description: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.

children.name: BookFormatType

A business entity type is a conceptual entity representing the legal form, the size, the main line of business, the position in the value chain, or any combination thereof, of an organization or business person.

http://purl...

children.name: BusinessFunction
children.description: The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation...

children.name: CarUsageType
children.description: A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.

children.name: ContactPointOption

children.name: DayOfWeek
children.description:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

children.name: DeliveryMethod

children.name: DigitalDocumentPermissionType

children.name: DigitalPlatformEnumeration
children.description: Enumerates some common technology platforms, for use with properties such as actionPlatform. It is not supposed to be comprehensive - when a suitable code is not enumerated here, textual or URL values can be used instead. These codes are at a fairly high level and do not deal with versioning and other nuance...

children.name: EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
children.description: Enumerates energy efficiency levels (also known as "classes" or "ratings") and certifications that are part of several international energy efficiency standards.

children.name: EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
children.description: Enumerates the EU energy efficiency classes A-G as well as A+, A++, and A+++ as defined in EU directive 2017/1369.

children.name: EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
children.description: Used to indicate whether a product is EnergyStar certified.

children.name: EventAttendanceModeEnumeration
children.description: An EventAttendanceModeEnumeration value is one of potentially several modes of organising an event, relating to whether it is online or offline.

children.name: GameAvailabilityEnumeration
children.description: For a VideoGame, such as used with a PlayGameAction, an enumeration of the kind of game availability offered.

children.name: GamePlayMode

children.name: GenderType

children.name: GovernmentBenefitsType

children.name: HealthAspectEnumeration

children.name: ItemAvailability

children.name: ItemListOrderType

children.name: LegalValueLevel

children.name: MapCategoryType

children.name: MeasurementTypeEnumeration
children.description: Enumeration of common measurement types (or dimensions), for example "chest" for a person, "inseam" for pants, "gauge" for screws, or "wheel" for bicycles.

children.name: BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration
children.description: Enumerates types (or dimensions) of a person's body measurements, for example for fitting of clothes.

children.name: WearableMeasurementTypeEnumeration
children.description: Enumerates common types of measurement for wearables products.

children.name: MedicalEnumeration
children.description: Enumerations related to health and the practice of medicine: A concept that is used to attribute a quality to another concept, as a qualifier, a collection of items or a listing of all of the elements of a set in medicine practice.

children.name: DrugCostCategory

children.name: DrugPregnancyCategory

children.name: DrugPrescriptionStatus

children.name: AnatomicalStructure
children.description: Any part of the human body, typically a component of an anatomical system. Organs, tissues, and cells are all anatomical structures.

children.name: Bone
children.description: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.

children.name: BrainStructure
children.description: Any anatomical structure which pertains to the soft nervous tissue functioning as the coordinating center of sensation and intellectual and nervous activity.

children.name: Joint
children.description: The anatomical location at which two or more bones make contact.

children.name: Ligament
children.description: A short band of tough, flexible, fibrous connective tissue that functions to connect multiple bones, cartilages, and structurally support joints.

children.name: Muscle
children.description: A muscle is an anatomical structure consisting of a contractile form of tissue that animals use to effect movement.

children.name: Nerve
children.description: A common pathway for the electrochemical nerve impulses that are transmitted along each of the axons.

children.name: Vessel

children.name: Artery
children.description: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood away from the heart.

children.name: LymphaticVessel
children.description: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries lymph fluid unidirectionally toward the heart.

children.name: Vein

children.name: AnatomicalSystem
children.description: An anatomical system is a group of anatomical structures that work together to perform a certain task. children.name: DrugClass

children.name: DrugCost

children.name: LifestyleModification
children.description: A process of care involving exercise, changes to diet, fitness routines, and other lifestyle changes aimed at improving a health condition.

children.name: Diet
children.description: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

children.name: PhysicalActivity
children.description: Any bodily activity that enhances or maintains physical fitness and overall health and wellness. Includes activity that is part of daily living and routine, structured exercise, and exercise prescribed as part of a medical treatment or recovery plan.

children.name: ExercisePlan
children.description: Fitness-related activity designed for a specific health-related purpose, including defined exercise routines as well as activity prescribed by a clinician.

children.name: MedicalCause
children.description: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign...

children.name: MedicalCondition
children.description: Any condition of the human body that affects the normal functioning of a person, whether physically or mentally. Includes diseases, injuries, disabilities, disorders, syndromes, etc.

children.name: InfectiousDisease
children.description: An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.

children.name: MedicalSignOrSymptom
children.description: Any feature associated or not with a medical condition. In medicine a symptom is generally subjective while a sign is objective.

children.name: MedicalSign
children.description: Any physical manifestation of a person's medical condition discoverable by objective diagnostic tests or physical examination.

children.name: VitalSign
children.description: Vital signs are measures of various physiological functions in order to assess the most basic body functions.

children.name: MedicalSymptom
children.description: Any complaint sensed and expressed by the patient (therefore defined as subjective)  like stomachache, lower-back pain, or fatigue.

children.name: MedicalContraindication
children.description: A condition or factor that serves as a reason to withhold a certain medical therapy. Contraindications can be absolute (there are no reasonable circumstances for undertaking a course of action) or relative (the patient is at higher risk of complications, but these risks may be outweighed by other considerations or mitigated by other measures).

children.name: MedicalDevice
children.description: Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.

children.name: MedicalGuideline
children.description: Any recommendation made by a standard society (e.g. ACC/AHA) or consensus statement that denotes how to diagnose and treat a particular condition. Note: this type should be used to tag the actual guideline recommendation; if the guideline recommendation occurs in a larger scholarly article, use MedicalScholarlyArticle to tag the overall article, not this type...

children.name: MedicalGuidelineContraindication
children.description: A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.

children.name: MedicalGuidelineRecommendation
children.description: A guideline recommendation that is regarded as efficacious and where quality of the data supporting the recommendation is sound.

children.name: MedicalIndication
children.description: A condition or factor that indicates use of a medical therapy, including signs, symptoms, risk factors, anatomical states, etc.

children.name: ApprovedIndication
children.description: An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.

children.name: PreventionIndication
children.description: An indication for preventing an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

children.name: TreatmentIndication
children.description: An indication for treating an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

children.name: MedicalIntangible
children.description: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.

children.name: DDxElement

children.name: DoseSchedule

children.name: RecommendedDoseSchedule

children.name: ReportedDoseSchedule
children.description: A patient-reported or observed dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.

children.name: DrugLegalStatus

children.name: DrugStrength

children.name: MedicalCode

children.name: PalliativeProcedure

children.name: PhysicalExam

children.name: SurgicalProcedure

children.name: TherapeuticProcedure
children.description: A medical procedure intended primarily for therapeutic purposes, aimed at improving a health condition.

children.name: MedicalTherapy
children.description: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. children.name: OccupationalTherapy
children.description: A treatment of people with physical, emotional, or social problems, using purposeful activity to help them overcome or learn to deal with their problems.

children.name: PalliativeProcedure
children.description: A medical procedure intended primarily for palliative purposes, aimed at relieving the symptoms of an underlying health condition.

children.name: PhysicalTherapy

children.name: RadiationTherapy

children.name: RespiratoryTherapy

children.name: PsychologicalTreatment

children.name: MedicalRiskCalculator

children.name: MedicalRiskScore

children.name: MedicalRiskFactor

children.name: MedicalObservationalStudy

In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator...

children.name: MedicalTrial
children.description: A medical trial is a type of medical study that uses a scientific process to compare the safety and efficacy of medical therapies or medical procedures.
