children.description: An eCommerce site.

children.name: PerformingGroup
children.description: A performance group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a circus.

children.name: DanceGroup
children.description: A dance group—for example, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater or Riverdance.

children.name: MusicGroup
children.description: A musical group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a choir. Can also be a solo musician.

children.name: TheaterGroup
children.description: A theater group or company, for example, the Royal Shakespeare Company or Druid Theatre.

children.name: Project
children.description:
An enterprise (potentially individual but typically collaborative), planned to achieve a particular aim.
Use properties from Organization, subOrganization/parentOrganization to indicate project sub-structures.

children.name: FundingAgency
children.description:
A FundingAgency is an organization that implements one or more FundingSchemes and manages
    the granting process (via Grants, typically MonetaryGrants).
    A funding agency is not always required for grant funding, e.g. philanthropic giving, corporate sponsorship etc...

children.name: ResearchProject
children.description: A Research project.

children.name: ResearchOrganization
children.description: A Research Organization (e.g. scientific institute, research company).

children.name: SearchRescueOrganization
children.description: A Search and Rescue organization of some kind.

children.name: SportsOrganization
children.description: Represents the collection of all sports organizations, including sports teams, governing bodies, and sports associations.

children.name: SportsTeam
children.description: Organization: Sports team.

children.name: WorkersUnion
children.description: A Workers Union (also known as a Labor Union, Labour Union, or Trade Union) is an organization that promotes the interests of its worker members by collectively bargaining with management, organizing, and political lobbying.

children.name: Person
children.description: A person (alive, dead, undead, or fictional).

children.name: Patient
children.description: A patient is any person recipient of health care services.

children.name: Place
children.description: Entities that have a somewhat fixed, physical extension.

children.name: Accommodation
children.description:
An accommodation is a place that can accommodate human beings, e.g. a hotel room, a camping pitch, or a meeting room. Many accommodations are for overnight stays, but this is not a mandatory requirement.
For more specific types of accommodations not defined in schema...

children.name: Apartment
children.description: An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).

children.name: CampingPitch
children.description:
A CampingPitch is an individual place for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically being part of a larger camping site, or Campground.

In British English a campsite, or campground, is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground...

children.name: House
children.description: A house is a building or structure that has the ability to be occupied for habitation by humans or other creatures (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House).

children.name: SingleFamilyResidence
children.description: Residence type: Single-family home.

children.name: Room
children.description:
A room is a distinguishable space within a structure, usually separated from other spaces by interior walls (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Room).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

children.name: HotelRoom
children.description:
A hotel room is a single room in a hotel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

children.name: MeetingRoom
children.description:
A meeting room, conference room, or conference hall is a room provided for singular events such as business conferences and meetings (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conference_hall).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema...

children.name: Suite
children.description:
A suite in a hotel or other public accommodation, denotes a class of luxury accommodations, the key feature of which is multiple rooms (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suite_(hotel)).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema...

children.name: AdministrativeArea
children.description: A geographical region, typically under the jurisdiction of a particular government.

children.name: City
children.description: A city or town.

children.name: Country
children.description: A country.

children.name: SchoolDistrict
children.description: A School District is an administrative area for the administration of schools.

children.name: State
children.description: A state or province of a country.

children.name: CivicStructure
children.description: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.

children.name: Airport
children.description: An airport.

children.name: Aquarium
children.description: Aquarium.

children.name: Beach
children.description: Beach.

children.name: BoatTerminal
children.description: A terminal for boats, ships, and other water vessels.

children.name: Bridge
children.description: A bridge.

children.name: BusStation
children.description: A bus station.

children.name: BusStop
children.description: A bus stop.

children.name: Campground
children.description:
A camping site, campsite, or Campground is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically containing individual CampingPitch locations. 

In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground...

children.name: Cemetery
children.description: A graveyard.

children.name: Crematorium
children.description: A crematorium.

children.name: EducationalOrganization
children.description: An educational organization.

children.name: EventVenue
children.description: An event venue.

children.name: FireStation
children.description: A fire station. With firemen.

children.name: GovernmentBuilding
children.description: A government building.

children.name: CityHall
children.description: A city hall.

children.name: Courthouse
children.description: A courthouse.

children.name: DefenceEstablishment
children.description: A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.

children.name: Embassy
children.description: An embassy.

children.name: LegislativeBuilding
children.description: A legislative building—for example, the state capitol.

children.name: Hospital
children.description: A hospital.

children.name: MovieTheater
children.description: A movie theater.

children.name: Museum
children.description: A museum.

children.name: MusicVenue
children.description: A music venue.

children.name: Park
children.description: A park.

children.name: ParkingFacility
children.description: A parking lot or other parking facility.

children.name: PerformingArtsTheater
children.description: A theater or other performing art center.

children.name: PlaceOfWorship
children.description: Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.

children.name: BuddhistTemple
children.description: A Buddhist temple.

children.name: Church
children.description: A church.

children.name: CatholicChurch
children.description: A Catholic church.

children.name: HinduTemple
children.description: A Hindu temple.

children.name: Mosque
children.description: A mosque.

children.name: Synagogue
children.description: A synagogue.

children.name: Playground
children.description: A playground.

children.name: PoliceStation
children.description: A police station.

children.name: PublicToilet
children.description: A public toilet is a room or small building containing one or more toilets (and possibly also urinals) which is available for use by the general public, or by customers or employees of certain businesses.

children.name: RVPark
children.description: A place offering space for "Recreational Vehicles", Caravans, mobile homes and the like.

children.name: StadiumOrArena
children.description: A stadium.

children.name: SubwayStation
children.description: A subway station.

children.name: TaxiStand
children.description: A taxi stand.

children.name: TrainStation
children.description: A train station.

children.name: Zoo
children.description: A zoo.

children.name: Landform
children.description: A landform or physical feature.  Landform elements include mountains, plains, lakes, rivers, seascape and oceanic waterbody interface features such as bays, peninsulas, seas and so forth, including sub-aqueous terrain features such as submersed mountain ranges, volcanoes, and the great ocean basins.

children.name: BodyOfWater
children.description: A body of water, such as a sea, ocean, or lake.

children.name: Canal
children.description: A canal, like the Panama Canal.

children.name: LakeBodyOfWater
children.description: A lake (for example, Lake Pontrachain).

children.name: OceanBodyOfWater
children.description: An ocean (for example, the Pacific).

children.name: Pond
children.description: A pond.

children.name: Reservoir
children.description: A reservoir of water, typically an artificially created lake, like the Lake Kariba reservoir.

children.name: RiverBodyOfWater
children.description: A river (for example, the broad majestic Shannon).

children.name: SeaBodyOfWater
children.description: A sea (for example, the Caspian sea).

children.name: Waterfall
children.description: A waterfall, like Niagara.

children.name: Continent
children.description: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).

children.name: Mountain
children.description: A mountain, like Mount Whitney or Mount Everest.

children.name: Volcano
children.description: A volcano, like Fujisan.

children.name: LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings
children.description: An historical landmark or building.

children.name: LocalBusiness
children.description: A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.

children.name: Residence
children.description: The place where a person lives.

children.name: ApartmentComplex
children.description: Residence type: Apartment complex.

children.name: GatedResidenceCommunity
children.description: Residence type: Gated community.

children.name: TouristAttraction
children.description: A tourist attraction.  In principle any Thing can be a TouristAttraction, from a Mountain and LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings to a LocalBusiness.  This Type can be used on its own to describe a general TouristAttraction, or be used as an additionalType to add tourist attraction properties to any other type...

children.name: TouristDestination
children.description: A tourist destination. In principle any Place can be a TouristDestination from a City, Region or Country to an AmusementPark or Hotel. This Type can be used on its own to describe a general TouristDestination, or be used as an additionalType to add tourist relevant properties to any other Place...

children.name: Product
children.description: Any offered product or service. For example: a pair of shoes; a concert ticket; the rental of a car; a haircut; or an episode of a TV show streamed online.

children.name: DietarySupplement
children.description: A product taken by mouth that contains a dietary ingredient intended to supplement the diet. Dietary ingredients may include vitamins, minerals, herbs or other botanicals, amino acids, and substances such as enzymes, organ tissues, glandulars and metabolites.

children.name: Drug
children.description: A chemical or biologic substance, used as a medical therapy, that has a physiological effect on an organism. Here the term drug is used interchangeably with the term medicine although clinical knowledge makes a clear difference between them.

children.name: IndividualProduct
children.description: A single, identifiable product instance (e.g. a laptop with a particular serial number).

children.name: ProductCollection
children.description: A set of products (either ProductGroups or specific variants) that are listed together e.g. in an Offer.

children.name: ProductGroup
children.description:
A ProductGroup represents a group of Products that vary only in certain well-described ways, such as by size, color, material etc.

While a ProductGroup itself is not directly offered for sale, the various varying products that it represents can be. The ProductGroup serves as a prototype or template, standing in for all of the products who have an isVariantOf relationship to it...

children.name: ProductModel
children.description: A datasheet or vendor specification of a product (in the sense of a prototypical description).

children.name: SomeProducts
children.description: A placeholder for multiple similar products of the same kind.

children.name: Vehicle
children.description: A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.

children.name: BusOrCoach
children.description: A bus (also omnibus or autobus) is a road vehicle designed to carry passengers. Coaches are luxury busses, usually in service for long distance travel.

children.name: Car
children.description: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.

children.name: Motorcycle
children.description: A motorcycle or motorbike is a single-track, two-wheeled motor vehicle.

children.name: MotorizedBicycle
children.description: A motorized bicycle is a bicycle with an attached motor used to power the vehicle, or to assist with pedaling.

children.name: StupidType
children.description: A StupidType for testing.

children.name: Taxon
children.description: A set of organisms asserted to represent a natural cohesive biological unit.
